of resource predictability in niche overlap between species for resources they share. Most examples are drawn from eleven North and South American bird communities, although the concepts and methodology are far more general. Next, the optimality of community structure is tested through parallel and convergent evolution on different continents with similar climates and habitats, and the direct influence of competitors on resource use is investigated by comparisons of species--poor island communities to species-rich mainland ones. Finally, the author discusses those sorts of environments in which the evolution of one species--one resource set is not achieved, and where alternative schemes of resource allocation, often involving several species that act ecologically as one, must be followed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBird populations. 0aBirdsxBehavior. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh  aMohave Desert.  aalgae.  abird densities.  abody size.  achaparral bird communities.  aclimate variables.  acommunity matrix.  adisplacement patterns.  aecological counterparts.  agrassland birds.  agrowth rates.  ahistorical effects.  ainterspecific territoriality.  aislands.  amixed species flocks.  anest sites.  apine-oak-juniper woodland.  aresource: difference.  aseabirds.  aseasonal changes.  aspecialists versus generalists.  atemporal territoriality.  aterritory.  avocalization.  awillow scrub habitat.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691209333zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209333423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691209333.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton Universi